ğŸ“Œ Singleton Design Pattern â€“ Eager Instantiation
ğŸ”· What is Singleton?
A Singleton is a design pattern that ensures:
â€¢	Only one object of a class is ever created.
â€¢	The same object is reused everywhere in the application.
________________________________________
ğŸŸ§ Eager Instantiation (Early Loading)
In eager instantiation, the Singleton object is created as soon as the class is loaded into memory, even before it is used.

Using a static block or directly creating the object using a static reference variable, we initialize the Singleton object at class loading time.
This object is stored in a private static reference variable like INSTANCE.
This complete process is called eager (or early) instantiation of a Singleton class.
----------------------------------------------
ğŸ“Œ Important Note
Since the Singleton object is created immediately when the class is loaded:
â€¢	There is no conditional check inside the static factory method (getInstance()).
â€¢	The static method always returns the same object without verifying whether it has already been created.
â€¢	Hence, there is no chance of thread switching during object creation.
â€¢	Therefore, eager instantiation is inherently thread-safe in a multithreaded environment.
________________________________________
ğŸŸ¨ Advantages of Eager Instantiation
â€¢	âœ” Simple implementation
â€¢	âœ” Thread-safe without synchronized blocks
â€¢	âœ” Easy to understand and use
________________________________________
ğŸŸ¥ Disadvantages
â€¢	âŒ Object is created even if the application never uses it
â€¢	âŒ Not suitable for objects that are heavy/expensive to create
â€¢	âŒ May waste memory if the instance is never required